","$\\mathrm{A}=0$ and $\\mathrm{B}=0$"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/uzHl0kYsCGoXD3inWyVtRr6GBZD_STGedw3XNkyoqkI.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>$\\begin{aligned}<br/>& \\mathrm{Y}_1=\\mathrm{A} \\cdot \\mathrm{~B}, \\mathrm{Y}_2=\\overline{\\mathrm{A}}+\\mathrm{B} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{Y}=\\overline{\\mathrm{Y}_1 \\cdot \\mathrm{Y}_2}=\\overline{\\mathrm{Y}}_1+\\overline{\\mathrm{Y}}_2 \\\\\n& \\mathrm{Y}=\\overline{\\mathrm{A} \\cdot \\mathrm{~B}}+\\overline{\\mathrm{A}+\\mathrm{B}} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{Y}=\\overline{\\mathrm{A}}+\\overline{\\mathrm{B}}+\\mathrm{A} \\cdot \\overline{\\mathrm{~B}}<br/>\\end{aligned}$<br/>$\\begin{array}{|c|c|c|} \\hline A & B & Y \\\\ \\hline 0 & 0 & 1 \\\\ \\hline 1 & 0 & 1 \\\\ \\hline 0 & 1 & 1 \\\\ \\hline 1 & 1 & 0 \\\\ \\hline \\end{array}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43531,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["AND gate","OR gate","NOR gate","NAND gate"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b7dc9b21-f736-4ac1-8595-5558b1416717-image.png\" style=\"width: 550px; height: 223px;\" /></p><p>According to the circuit,</p><p>Output<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mover><mrow><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#175;</mo></mover><mo>+</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#175;</mo></mover></mrow><mo>&#175;</mo></mover></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right left right left right left right left right left right left\" columnspacing=\"0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em\" rowspacing=\"3pt\"><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo accent=\"false\">&#175;</mo></mover><mo>&#8901;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo accent=\"false\">&#175;</mo></mover></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#8901;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>Thus, the given circuit is a AND gate.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43516,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>A</mi></mtd><mtd><mi>B</mi></mtd><mtd><mi>Y</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>A</mi></mtd><mtd><mi>B</mi></mtd><mtd><mi>Y</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>A</mi></mtd><mtd><mi>B</mi></mtd><mtd><mi>Y</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>A</mi></mtd><mtd><mi>B</mi></mtd><mtd><mi>Y</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>When both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math> have logical value &lsquo;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>&rsquo; both diode are reverse bias and current will flow in resistor hence output will be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math> volt i.e. logical value &lsquo;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>&rsquo;.</p><p>In all other case conduction will take place, hence output will be zero volt i.e. logical value &lsquo;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn></math>&rsquo;. So truth table is</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>A</mi></mtd><mtd><mi>B</mi></mtd><mtd><mi>Y</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>Thus, given circuit is equivalent to an AND gate.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43558,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#946;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>&#945;</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>&#945;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>&#946;</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>&#945;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#946;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>&#945;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>&#946;</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>&#946;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>C</mi></msub><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>E</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mi>&#946;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>C</mi></msub><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>B</mi></msub></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>E</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>C</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>C</mi></msub><mrow><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>C</mi></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>C</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>&#946;</mi></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>&#946;</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>&#946;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43524,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["Both&nbsp;A&nbsp;and R&nbsp;true, and R&nbsp;is correct explanation of A.","Both A&nbsp;and R&nbsp;are true but R&nbsp;is NOT the correct explanation of A.","A is true but R&nbsp;is false.","A is false but R&nbsp;is true."],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>A <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>&#8208;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mo>&#8208;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></math>&nbsp;transistor&nbsp;has more electrons than holes, and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mo>&#8208;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>&#8208;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math>&nbsp;transistor&nbsp;has more holes than electrons. When a voltage is applied,&nbsp;then the movement of electrons is greater than holes. Therefore, conduction current in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>&#8208;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mo>&#8208;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></math>&nbsp;transistor&nbsp;is more than that in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mo>&#8208;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>&#8208;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math>&nbsp;transistor.</p><p>Both statements are true.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43579,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cffc4e4f-1811-4c7d-b3de-9b43a8e71b8a-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 83px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/45924226-2de9-4f9e-86aa-f450cfd9342f-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 79px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e68c0123-922d-4b9a-a9bc-3578d144e8dd-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 85px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/67f726e3-f664-4e4b-828e-9028bf886eeb-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 81px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Truth table</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fd81abcb-2d8b-44fc-9f26-f71f545fdf21-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 214px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mrow><mover><mi>A</mi><mo>&#175;</mo></mover><mo>&#183;</mo><mover><mi>B</mi><mo>&#175;</mo></mover></mrow><mo>&#175;</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mover><mover><mi>A</mi><mo>&#175;</mo></mover><mo>&#175;</mo></mover><mo>+</mo><mover><mover><mi>B</mi><mo>&#175;</mo></mover><mo>&#175;</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>B</mi></math></p><p><img height=\"161\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9bf02c37-6433-4e66-a225-996f78dff4d6-image.png\" width=\"691\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43523,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Semiconductors","question":"","options":["It is two terminal device which conducts current in both directions.","It is two terminal device which conducts current in one direction only","It does not conduct current gives an initial deflection which decays to zero.","It is three terminal device which conducts current in one direction only between central terminal and either of the remaining two terminals"],"answer":1,"solution":"A diode is a two-terminal device that conducts current in forward bias and does not conduct current in reverse bias i.e. it conducts current in one direction only.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 1)","image":null}]